{"title_page": "2020 in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date = November 2018}}\n{{Year in United Kingdom|2020|label1=Individual countries of the United Kingdom|data1=[[2020 in England|England]] {{!}} [[2020 in Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland]] {{!}} [[2020 in Scotland|Scotland]] {{!}} [[2020 in Wales|Wales]]|label2=Popular culture |data2=<div>\n[[Football in the United Kingdom|Football]]: [[2019\u201320 in English football|England]] {{!}} [[2019\u201320 in Scottish football|Scotland]] {{!}} [[2019\u201320 in Welsh football|Wales]]<br />\n[[2020 British Grand Prix]]<br />\n[[2020 English cricket season]]<br />\n[[2020 in British television]]<br />\n[[2020 in British music]]<br />\n[[2020 in British radio]]<br />\n[[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020|UK in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020]]\n</div>}}\nEvents from the year '''2020 in the United Kingdom'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[Monarch of the United Kingdom|Monarch]] \u2013 [[Elizabeth II]]\n*[[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] \u2013 [[Boris Johnson]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]])\n*[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] \u2013 [[List of MPs elected in the 2019 United Kingdom general election|58th]]\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January ===\n*4 January \u2013 The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] warns British nationals against all but essential travel to [[Iran]] and [[Iraq]], following [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|a US airstrike in Baghdad]] the previous day in which Iranian general [[Qasem Soleimani]] was killed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50991778 |title=Qasem Soleimani: Foreign Office hardens Iran and Iraq travel advice |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=4 January 2020 |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n*5 January \u2013 Boris Johnson says \"we will not lament\" Qasem Soleimani's death as he calls for \"de-escalation from all sides\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51001236 |title=Qasem Soleimani: PM 'will not lament' Iranian general's death |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 January 2020 |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n*6 January\n**[[Reynhard Sinaga]], described as \"the most prolific rapist in British legal history\", is sentenced to life in prison with a minimum term of 30 years, after being found guilty of raping or sexually assaulting 48 men in Manchester. Police believe he may have been responsible for assaulting a total of nearly 200 victims.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/06/reynhard-sinaga-jailed-life-drugging-raping-men-manchester |title=Reynhard Sinaga: man jailed for life for raping dozens of men in Manchester |work=The Guardian|date=6 January 2020 |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Downing Street]] states that Britain will not support U.S. President [[Donald Trump]]'s threat to bomb Iranian cultural and heritage sites.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/06/no-10-uk-would-not-back-us-bombing-of-iranian-cultural-sites|title=UK would not back US bombing of Iran cultural sites \u2013 No 10|work=The Guardian|date=6 January 2020 |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n*7 January \u2013 The [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|Labour Party leadership election]] formally begins, with the new leader scheduled to be announced on 4 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51000133 |title=Labour leadership: Result will be announced on 4 April |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 January 2020 |accessdate=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n*8 January \u2013 [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]], and [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]], announce that they plan to \"step back as senior members\" of [[British Royal family|Britain's royal family]], and divide their time between the UK and North America.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51040751 |title=Harry and Meghan to step back as senior royals |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 January 2020 |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n*9 January \n**The [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] gives its third and final backing to the [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill 2019\u201320|Withdrawal Agreement Bill]], voting 330 to 231 in favour; the bill now passes to the [[House of Lords (United Kingdom)|House of Lords]] for scrutiny.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51051178 |title=MPs give final backing to Brexit bill |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=9 January 2020 |accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n**The UK and Irish governments publish [[2020 Northern Ireland Agreement|a deal]] aimed at restoring the [[Northern Ireland Executive]]; the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] gives its backing to the agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Andrew |last=Madden |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/dup-accept-governments-draft-agreement-to-restore-stormont-sinn-fein-studying-text-38849112.html |title=DUP accept governments' draft agreement to restore Stormont, Sinn Fein 'studying' text |work=Belfast Telegraph |publisher=Independent News and Media |date=9 January 2020 |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n*10 January \u2013 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] gives its backing to [[2020 Northern Ireland Agreement|a deal]] to restore power-sharing government to Northern Ireland for the first time since 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51068774 |title=Sinn F\u00e9in agrees to rejoin NI government after deal |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=10 January 2020 |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n*11 January  \n**The [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] reconvenes after a three-year hiatus; [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] leader [[Arlene Foster]] is appointed [[First Minister of Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland's first minister]], while [[Sinn Fein]]'s [[Michelle O'Neill]] is appointed [[Deputy First Minister of Northern Ireland|deputy first minister]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-51077397 |title=Stormont deal: Arlene Foster and Michelle O'Neill new top NI ministers |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 January 2020 |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Robert Macaire (diplomat)|Robert Macaire]], the British ambassador to [[Iran]], is briefly detained in Iran after attending a vigil for those killed on [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]]. Iran summoned him to appear at [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Iran)|its foreign ministry]] the following day after saying he had been \"an unknown foreigner in an illegal gathering\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51077897 |title=Iran plane crash: Britain condemns Tehran's arrest of UK ambassador |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 January 2020 |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n*13 January \u2013 Following a meeting of senior royals, [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] agrees to a \"period of transition\" during which the Duke and Duchess of Sussex will spend time in Canada and the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51099102 |title=Queen agrees 'transition' to new role for Harry and Meghan |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 January 2020 |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n*14 January\n**The government agrees a rescue package for troubled regional airline [[Flybe]] to stop it going into administration.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51113895 |title=Flybe: Government strikes a deal to rescue troubled airline |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 January 2020 |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n**Boris Johnson formally rejects [[First Minister of Scotland|Scottish First Minister]] [[Nicola Sturgeon]]'s request for a [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|second independence referendum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-51106796 |title=Scottish independence: Johnson rejects Sturgeon's indyref2 demand |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 January 2020 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n*16 January \u2013 Legislation is drafted before Parliament allowing the use of [[Professional video camera|television cameras]] during trials at [[Crown Court]]s in England and Wales, but only the [[judge]]s will be filmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51110206 |title=TV cameras to be allowed in Crown Courts in England and Wales |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 January 2020 |accessdate=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n*17 January \u2013 Construction begins on [[Dogger Bank Wind Farm]], which will become the world's largest offshore wind farm when complete, with 260-metre high turbines generating a combined 3.6 gigawatts and supplying 4.5 million homes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/amp/2020/01/17/work-starts-on-huge-wind-farm-that-could-power-4point5-million-homes.html |title=Work starts on world's 'largest offshore wind farm' that could power 4.5 million homes|publisher=CNBC|date=17 January 2020 |accessdate=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n*18 January \u2013 [[Buckingham Palace]] confirms that from spring 2020 the Duke and Duchess of Sussex will no longer use their royal titles and will no longer receive public funds for their royal duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51163865 |title=Harry and Meghan lose funding and drop HRH titles |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=18 January 2020 |accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n*21 January \u2013 The [[Office of Rail and Road]] announces that [[Network Rail]] is being investigated over its poor performance on routes used by train operators [[Arriva Rail North]] and [[TransPennine Express]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/network-rail-being-investigated-for-poor-performance-11914036 |title=Network Rail being investigated for 'poor performance' |publisher=Sky News|date=21 January 2020 |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*22 January \u2013 Boris Johnson's EU withdrawal deal successfully completes its passage through parliament, with the [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020|EU Withdrawal Agreement Bill]] being voted through without change, after several amendments proposed by the House of Lords are rejected.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51214761 |title=Brexit: UK has 'crossed Brexit finish line', says Boris Johnson |date=22 January 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n*23 January\n**Parliamentary ratification of Boris Johnson's EU withdrawal deal is completed with [[Royal Assent]] being given to the [[European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Act 2020|EU Withdrawal Agreement Bill]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/20200123IPR70904/brexit-the-withdrawal-agreement-passes-the-first-european-parliament-test |title=Brexit: the Withdrawal Agreement passes the first European Parliament test |date=23 January 2020 |work=News |publisher=European Parliament}}</ref>\n**An [[2002 Dudley earthquake|earthquake]] of 3.0 magnitude is recorded by the [[British Geological Survey]] in [[Stockton-on-Tees]], [[County Durham]], just before 6am.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jan/23/teesside-shaken-by-earthquake-stockton-durham |title=Teesside shaken by 3.0-magnitude earthquake |work=The Guardian|date=23 January 2020 |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n*24 January\n**The UK's EU withdrawal agreement is signed by both parties; firstly in the morning in [[Brussels]], by [[European Council]] president [[Charles Michel]] and [[European Commission]] president [[Ursula von der Leyen]] for the EU, then after travelling on the [[Eurostar]] in a diplomatic case, in [[London]] in the afternoon by Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] for the UK.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51244126 |title=Brexit: Boris Johnson signs withdrawal agreement in Downing Street |date=24 January 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/24/sombre-eu-leaders-sign-brexit-withdrawal-agreement |title='Fantastic moment': Boris Johnson signs Brexit withdrawal deal |date=24 January 2020 |last1=Proctor |first1=Kate |last2=Boffey |first2=Daniel |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n**Police announce that live [[Facial recognition system|facial recognition technology]] will be rolled out across London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-security-cameras/police-to-roll-out-live-facial-recognition-cameras-in-london-idUKKBN1ZN1H5 |title=Police to roll out live facial recognition cameras in London |publisher=Reuters|date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n*25 January \u2013 A newly-appointed member of the [[Grenfell Tower Inquiry|Grenfell Tower fire public enquiry panel]] resigns after being linked to the company which supplied cladding for the block.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51252297 |title=Grenfell Tower inquiry member Benita Mehra resigns |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=25 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n*27 January \u2013 The Health Secretary, [[Matt Hancock]], tells the House of Commons that 200 British citizens trapped in [[Wuhan]], [[China]], will be offered repatriation to the UK, in light of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak in Hubei|coronavirus outbreak there]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/27/britons-in-wuhan-will-be-offered-help-to-leave-hancock-tells-mps |title=Britons in Wuhan will be offered help to leave, Hancock tells MPs |work=The Guardian|date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n*28 January \u2013 The Prime Minister approves a limited \"non-core\" role for China's [[Huawei]] in Britain's [[5G]] mobile network, resisting U.S. pressure to exclude the company on fears China could use it to steal data.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/jan/28/boris-johnson-gives-green-light-for-huawei-5g-infrastructure-role |title=Boris Johnson gives green light for Huawei 5G infrastructure role |work=The Guardian|date=28 January 2020 |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n*29 January\n**[[British Airways]] suspends all flights to and from mainland China with immediate effect, due to the ongoing coronavirus threat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/29/evacuation-of-britons-in-coronavirus-hit-hubei-could-begin-thursday |title=Britons evacuated due to coronavirus to be quarantined |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper==The Guardian |date=29 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n**Transport Secretary [[Grant Shapps]] announces that troubled train operator [[Arriva Rail North]] will be brought under government control from 1 March following a prolonged period of delays and poor performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-51298820 |title=Troubled rail firm Northern brought under government control |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=29 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n**''[[The Guardian]]'' announces that it will no longer accept advertising from oil and gas companies, becoming the first major global news organisation to institute an outright ban on taking money from the fossil fuel industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/jan/29/guardian-to-ban-advertising-from-fossil-fuel-firms-climate-crisis |title=Guardian to ban advertising from fossil fuel firms |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[European Parliament]] ratifies the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] in Brussels, ensuring that if the United Kingdom leaves the European Union, as scheduled, at 23:00 GMT on 31 January 2020, they will do so with a deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brexit: European Parliament overwhelmingly backs terms of UK's exit|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51287430|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n*31 January\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The first two cases of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus (2019-nCoV) in the United Kingdom]] are confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-51325192|title=Two coronavirus cases confirmed in UK|date=2020-01-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n**The United Kingdom and [[Gibraltar]] leave the [[European Union]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Brexit: UK leaves the European Union |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51333314 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=31 January 2019}}</ref> beginning an 11-month transition period, during which they remain in the Single Market and Customs Union.\n\n===February===\n*1 February \u2013 [[Austria]], [[Germany]], and [[Slovenia]] confirm they will not extradite their nationals if they are accused of crimes in the UK.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/three-european-countries-refuse-uk-130000250.html Three European countries say they will refuse UK extradition requests now Brexit has happened] by Thomas Colson, Business Insider, 1 February 2020</ref>\n*2 February \u2013 A man is shot dead by police in South London after a [[2020 Streatham stabbing|stabbing incident]] on [[Streatham High Road]]; police treat the incident as [[Terrorism in the United Kingdom|terrorist]]-related.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-51349664 |title=Streatham attack: Man shot dead by police after stabbings in London |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2 February 2020 |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n*4 February \u2013 In London, Prime Minister Boris Johnson, naturalist [[David Attenborough|Sir David Attenborough]], and Italian Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] launch the [[COP26|26th session of the Conference of the Parties]] (COP26), a major UN climate summit to be held in Glasgow in November 2020.<ref name=BBC_51366123/> Johnson announces, subject to consultation, that coal power could be phased out by 2024, a year earlier than previously planned and the phase-out of new petrol and diesel vehicles could be brought forward from 2040 to 2035.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/02/04/coal-power-phased-2024-boris-johnson-says-uk-has-duty-fight/|title=Coal power to be phased out by 2024 as Boris Johnson says UK has duty to fight climate change as first industrialised nation|newspaper=Telegraph|language=en|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-05|last1=Yorke|first1=Harry}}</ref><ref name=BBC_51366123>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-51366123|title=Petrol and diesel car sales ban brought forward to 2035|website=BBC News|language=en|date=2020-02-04|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> He also reaffirms the UK's commitment to reaching net zero carbon by 2050.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-launches-un-climate-summit-in-the-uk|title=PM launches UN Climate Summit in the UK|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n*6 February \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A third case of coronavirus is confirmed in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51398039|title=Coronavirus: Third case confirmed in the UK\n|website=BBC News|language=en|date=2020-02-06|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n*7 February \u2013 [[Buckingham Palace]] announces that the wedding of [[Princess Beatrice of York]] and [[Edoardo Mapelli Mozzi]] will take place on 29 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51415860 |title=Princess Beatrice: Royal wedding to be held on 29 May |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n*8\u20139 February \u2013 [[Storm Ciara]] hits the United Kingdom, bringing winds of up to {{convert|80|mph|abbr=on}}.\n*9 February \u2013 A British Airways [[Boeing 747]] aircraft makes the fastest ever subsonic New York JFK to London Heathrow crossing, achieved in 4 hours 56 minutes. It reaches ground speeds of up to 825&nbsp;mph by riding the jet stream bringing [[Storm Ciara]] to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-51433720|title=Storm helps plane beat transatlantic flight record|work=BBC News|date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\n*10 February\n**The government confirms it has begun to study the feasibility of a [[Irish Sea Bridge|Scotland-Northern Ireland bridge]], with project cost estimates of \u00a315\u201320bn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/10/boris-johnson-northern-ireland-scotland-bridge-plan-being-actively-looked-into-no-10|title=Government 'actively looking into' Scotland-Northern Ireland bridge|website=The Guardian|language=en|date=2020-02-10|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51443191|title=Work 'under way' into Scotland-Northern Ireland bridge feasibility|website=BBC News|language=en|date=2020-02-10|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18224365.whitehall-officials-begin-scoping-work-boris-bridge-linking-scotland-n-ireland/|title=Whitehall officials begin 'scoping work' on Boris Bridge linking Scotland and Northern Ireland|website=The Herald|language=en|date=2020-02-10|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n**In a \"historic\" decision, councillors reject a proposed expansion of [[Bristol Airport]], by 18 votes to seven, on the grounds that it would exacerbate [[climate change]], damage the health of local people, and harm flora and fauna.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/feb/11/plan-to-expand-bristol-airport-rejected-after-climate-protests|title=Plan to expand Bristol airport rejected after climate protests|website=The Guardian|language=en|date=2020-02-11|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n*11 February \u2013 \n**In the wake of the Streatham stabbing, the [[Terrorist Offenders Bill 2020|Terrorist Offenders Bill]], designed to end the early release of prisoners convicted of terrorist offences, is presented to parliament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51453418 |title=Emergency terror law presented to Parliament |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 February 2020 |accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n**Following a review of the project, Prime Minister Boris Johnson announces that the controversial high-speed rail link [[High Speed 2|HS2]] will be built.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51461597 |title=HS2 go-ahead controversial and difficult, admits Boris Johnson |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 February 2020 |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n*12 February\n**The Terrorist Offenders Bill passes unopposed through the [[House of Commons (United Kingdom)|House of Commons]] to complete the first stage of the process to becoming law.<ref name=Independent-2020-02-12>{{cite news|first=Ashley |last=Cowburn |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/streatham-attack-terrorist-mp-jail-bill-commons-a9332496.html |title=Streatham attack: Bill stopping early release of jailed terrorists passes unopposed in Commons |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=12 February 2020 |accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces plans to extend the remit of the media regulator [[Ofcom]] to include internet and social media content in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|first=Alex |last=Hern |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/feb/12/ofcom-to-be-put-in-charge-of-regulating-internet-in-uk |title=Ofcom to be put in charge of regulating internet in UK |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 February 2020 |accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n*13 February\n**[[Boris Johnson]] carries out a [[2020 British cabinet reshuffle|cabinet reshuffle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49043973 |title=Cabinet reshuffle: Who is in Boris Johnson's new cabinet? |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 February 2020 |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Sajid Javid]] resigns as [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]. He is succeeded by [[Rishi Sunak]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/whos-in-and-whos-out-in-boris-johnsons-reshuffle-11932951|title=Sajid Javid on shock resignation as chancellor: 'No self-respecting minister would accept those conditions'|publisher=Sky News|date=13 February 2020|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n*16 February \u2013 [[Storm Dennis]]: A record high number of flood warnings are declared over England, with 600 in place by the evening.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51519635|title=Storm Dennis: Major incidents declared in south Wales and Herefordshire|publisher=BBC News|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/live/2020/feb/16/storm-dennis-met-office-issues-red-warning-south-wales-floods-live-updates?page=with:block-5e4938be8f086a28115acb1a#block-5e4938be8f086a28115acb1a|title=Record number of flood warnings in place|work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> Police declare major incidents in a number of regions, including south Wales, after towns and villages north of [[Cardiff]] receive more than a month's worth of rainfall in 24 hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/16/storm-dennis-prompts-life-threatening-flood-warnings-in-south-wales|title=Storm Dennis: police declare major incident in south Wales|work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n*17 February \u2013 [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business and Energy Secretary]] and [[COP26]] President [[Alok Sharma]] announces \u00a31.2 billion in funding for a new [[supercomputer]] to improve weather and climate models in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-51504002|title=Met Office forecasters set for 'billion pound' supercomputer|publisher=BBC News|date=17 February 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/about-us/press-office/news/corporate/2020/supercomputer-funding-2020|title=\u00a31.2 Billion for weather and climate supercomputer|publisher=The Met Office|date=17 February 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n*20 February \u2013 A new [[Bank of England \u00a320 note|\u00a320]] [[polymer banknote]] enters circulation. Featuring the face of artist [[J. M. W. Turner|JMW Turner]], it joins the updated and more secure [[Bank of England \u00a35 note|\u00a35]] and [[Bank of England \u00a310 note|\u00a310]] notes that were introduced in 2016 and 2017, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51559349|title=New polymer \u00a320 featuring painter Turner enters circulation|publisher=BBC News|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n*25 February \u2013 A landmark study shows that life expectancy in England has stalled for the first time in more than 100 years and that health inequalities are growing wider than a decade ago. The study said that this can largely be attributed to the [[United Kingdom government austerity programme|UK government's austerity policies]].<ref>{{cite news |last= Boseley |first= Sarah |date= 25 February 2020 |title= Austerity blamed for life expectancy stalling for first time in century |url= https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/feb/24/austerity-blamed-for-life-expectancy-stalling-for-first-time-in-century |work= The Guardian |access-date= 1 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Tolhurst |first= Alain |date= 25 February 2020 |title= Austerity blamed for 'flatlining' life expectancy and worsening health inequalities over past decade |url= https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/health-and-care/news/110126/austerity-blamed-%E2%80%98flatlining%E2%80%99-life-expectancy-and-worsening |work= PoliticsHome |access-date= 1 March 2020}}</ref>\n*27 February \n**Campaigners win a Court of Appeal ruling over controversial plans for a third runway at [[Heathrow Airport]], on environmental grounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51658693 |title=Climate campaigners win Heathrow expansion case |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=27 February 2020 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n**A study is released that links increases in [[Mental distress|psychological distress]] and [[Major depressive disorder|clinical depression]] with [[Universal Credit]].<ref>{{cite news |last= Richardson |first= Hannah |date= 28 February 2020 |title= Thousands of depression cases 'linked to universal credit' |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-51664792 |work= BBC News |access-date= 28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Butler |first= Patrick |date= 27 February 2020 |title= Universal credit linked to rise in psychological stress, study finds |url= https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/feb/27/universal-credit-linked-psychological-stress-increase-study-benefits-uk |work= The Guardian |access-date= 28 February 2020}}</ref>\n*28 February \u2013[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The first British death from the disease is confirmed by the [[Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare|Japanese Health Ministry]]; a man [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|quarantined]] on the ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' cruise ship.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/28/first-briton-dies-from-coronavirus-japanese-media-report-diamond-princess |title=First British coronavirus death confirmed|work=The Guardian|date=28 February 2020 |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n*29 February\n**The [[Home Office]]'s top civil servant, [[Sir Philip Rutnam]], resigns and says he plans to claim [[constructive dismissal]] by the government following a series of clashes with the [[Home Secretary]], [[Priti Patel]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51687287 |title=Home Office boss quits over 'campaign against him' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=29 February 2020 |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson announces that he and his partner, [[Carrie Symonds]] are expecting a baby in the summer, and that they are engaged.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51691434 |title=Boris Johnson and Carrie Symonds engaged and expecting baby |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=29 February 2020 |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n*2 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government holds a [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBRA]] meeting to discuss its preparations and response to the coronavirus, as the number of UK cases jumps to 36.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51700604 |title=Coronavirus: Widespread transmission in UK 'highly likely' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*3 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government publishes its action plan for dealing with coronavirus. This includes scenarios ranging from a milder pandemic to a \"severe prolonged pandemic [[Spanish flu|as experienced in 1918]]\" and warns that a fifth of the national workforce could be absent from work during the infection's peak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51718917 |title=Coronavirus: Up to fifth of UK workers 'off sick at same time' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/03/uk-government-coronavirus-plans-strip-fire-and-police-to-essentials-covid-19 |title=UK coronavirus plans would strip police and fire services to essentials |work=The Guardian|date=3 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*5 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The airline [[Flybe]] collapses into administration, due in part to the impact of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51746564 |title=Collapsed Flybe tells passengers not to travel to airports |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The first death from coronavirus in the UK is confirmed,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51759602 |title=Coronavirus: Older patient becomes first virus fatality in UK |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> as the number of cases exceeds 100, with a total of 115 having tested positive. England's [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]], [[Chris Whitty]], tells MPs that the UK has now moved to the second stage of dealing with COVID-19 \u2013 from \"containment\" to the \"delay\" phase.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/05/more-than-a-hundred-people-in-uk-infected-with-coronavirus |title=More than a hundred people in UK infected with coronavirus |work=The Guardian|date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n*6 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The Prime Minister announces \u00a346 million in funding for research into a coronavirus vaccine and rapid diagnostic tests. During a visit to a laboratory in Bedfordshire, he says: \"It looks like there will be a substantial period of disruption where we have to deal with this outbreak.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/06/coronavirus-update-latest-live-news-symptoms-cases-global-infection-rate-uk-usa-australia-italy-china-updates?page=with:block-5e624ca98f087df56e4c37f9#block-5e624ca98f087df56e4c37f9 |title=Coronavirus latest updates |work=The Guardian|date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n*8 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A third death from coronavirus is reported, at [[North Manchester General Hospital]], as the number of cases in the UK reaches 273, the largest single-day increase so far.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51796072 |title=Coronavirus: Man in his 60s becomes third UK death |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 March 2020 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n*9 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[FTSE 100]] plunges by more than 8 percent, its largest intraday fall since 2008, amid concerns over the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cityam.com/coronavirus-ftse-100-plunges-on-open-after-oil-prices-crash-30-per-cent/ |title=Coronavirus: FTSE 100 plunges after oil prices crash 30 per cent |work=City AM |publisher=City AM |date=9 March 2020 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*10 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Health minister [[Nadine Dorries]] tests positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51827356 |title=Coronavirus: Health minister Nadine Dorries tests positive |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*11 March\n**The [[Bank of England]] cuts its baseline interest rate from 0.75% to 0.25%, back down to the lowest level in history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51831004 |title=UK interest rates cut in emergency move |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Rishi Sunak]], presents the Johnson Government's [[March 2020 United Kingdom budget|first budget]], which includes \u00a330 billion in measures to protect the economy from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-budget/uk-pledges-30-billion-to-protect-economy-from-coronavirus-idUKKBN20Y007 |title=UK pledges \u00a330 billion to protect economy from coronavirus |work=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51835306 |title=Budget 2020: Chancellor unveils \u00a330bn coronavirus package |work=BBC News|publisher=BBC News|date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/11/key-points-from-budget-2020-at-a-glance |title=Key points from budget 2020 \u2013 at a glance |work=The Guardian|date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*12 March \u2013 Following a series of recent major falls, the FTSE100 plunges yet again, this time by over 10%, its biggest drop since 1987.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51829852 |title=Coronavirus: Global stocks plunge as coronavirus fears spread |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live?page=with:block-5e6a636e8f08c2df6d278620#block-5e6a636e8f08c2df6d278620 |title=FTSE 100 suffers second worst day ever after 10.87% plunge \u2013 business live |work=The Guardian|date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref> Other markets around the world are similarly affected by ongoing economic turmoil.\n*13 March \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Premier League]] [[2019\u201320 Premier League|2019\u20132020 season]] is suspended, amid a growing list of worldwide sporting cancellations and postponements due to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Elections including the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections|English local elections]], [[2020 London mayoral election|London mayoral election]] and [[2020 England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections|police and crime commissioner elections]], scheduled for May 2020, are postponed for a year because of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=Coronavirus: English local elections postponed for a year |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n*14 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A further 10 people are reported to have died from COVID-19, almost doubling the UK death toll from 11 to 21. The government's aim for a \"[[herd immunity]]\" approach generates controversy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/uk-herd-immunity-coronavirus-who-margaret-harris-a4387346.html |title=UK's 'herd immunity' approach to tackling coronavirus questioned by World Health Organisation |work=Evening Standard|date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-51892402 |title=Coronavirus: Scientists say UK virus strategy is 'risking lives' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://maths.qmul.ac.uk/~vnicosia/UK_scientists_statement_on_coronavirus_measures.pdf |title=Public request to take stronger measures of socialdistancing across the UK with immediate effect |work=Queen Mary University of London |publisher=Queen Mary University of London |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Vice President of the United States]], [[Mike Pence]], announces the US is to extend its European [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States#Travel and entry restrictions|coronavirus travel ban]] to include the UK from 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51891662 |title=Coronavirus: US to extend travel ban to UK and Ireland |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: UK retailers release a joint letter asking customers not to panic buy products after some supermarkets sell out of items such as pasta, hand gel and toilet paper.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51883440 |title=Coronavirus: Supermarkets ask shoppers to be 'considerate' and stop panic buying |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*15 March \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] advises against \"all but essential travel\" to the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/15/coronavirus-latest-updates-trump-tests-negative-as-spain-orders-nationwide-lockdown-uk-us-australia-italy-europe-global-economy?page=with:block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed#block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed |title=UK advises against 'all but essential' travel to US |work=The Guardian|date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] says that every UK resident over the age of 70 will be told \"within the coming weeks\" to self-isolate for \"a very long time\" to shield them from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873 |title=Coronavirus: Isolation for over-70s 'within weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government announces plans to hold daily televised press conferences to update the public on the fight against the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]], starting on Monday 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51901818 |title=Coronavirus: Downing Street to give daily update on fight against outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*16 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]:  The UK death toll from the coronavirus pandemic reaches 55, with the number of cases of the illness passing 1,500.<ref name=avoid>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |title=Coronavirus: PM says everyone should avoid office, pubs and travelling |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson advises everyone in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others to curb coronavirus, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions are urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and will be asked to self-isolate within days.<ref name=avoid/>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The BBC delays its planned changes to TV licences for the over-75s from June to August because of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |title=Coronavirus: BBC delays over-75 TV licence fee changes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*17 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: NHS England announces that all non-urgent operations in England will be postponed from 15 April to free up 30,000 beds to help tackle the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Hashem Abedi, brother of [[Manchester Arena bombing|Manchester Arena bomber]] [[Salman Abedi]], is found guilty of murdering 22 people in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-51926162 |title=Manchester Arena bombing: Hashem Abedi guilty of 22 murders |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The Chancellor, Rishi Sunak, announces that \u00a3330bn will be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian|date=17 March 2020 |access